Ruslan Borysovych Khomchak (Ukrainian: Русла́н Бори́сович Хомча́к; born 5 June 1967) is a [Ukrainian](/Ukraine) [Colonel-general](/Colonel-general). He currently holds the position of First Deputy Secretary of the [National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine](/National_Security_and_Defense_Council_of_Ukraine) [2], a role he assumed after a notable tenure as the [Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine](/Chief_Commander_of_Armed_Forces_(Ukraine)). Until 28 March 2020, he concurrently served as the [Chief of the General Staff](/Chief_of_the_General_Staff_(Ukraine)).

From 21 May 2019, Khomchak held the dual responsibility of Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine and Chief of the General Staff. However, on 28 March 2020, President [Volodymyr Zelensky](/Volodymyr_Zelensky) issued a decree that separated these two distinct roles. [5] On that same day, Zelensky relieved Khomchak of his duties as Chief of the General Staff, appointing him Chief Commander of the Armed Forces. Concurrently, [Serhiy Korniychuk](/Serhiy_Korniychuk) was appointed as the new Chief of the General Staff. [5]

Later, on 27 July 2021, Ruslan Khomchak was dismissed from his position as Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine [3] and subsequently appointed as the First Deputy Secretary of the [National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine](/National_Security_and_Defense_Council_of_Ukraine). [2]

#### Biography

Born in [Lviv](/Lviv) on 5 June 1967, [7] Khomchak's military career began after his graduation from the [Moscow Higher Military Command School](/Moscow_Higher_Military_Command_School) in 1988. He initially served within the [Soviet Army](/Soviet_Army), specifically in the Soviet Artillery Corps. His early service was primarily with a self-propelled artillery unit equipped with the [2S3 Akatsiya](/2S3_Akatsiya) self-propelled howitzer. [7] Between 1988 and 1992, Khomchak's assignments took him to various locations, including [East Germany](/East_Germany), the [Uzbek SSR](/Uzbek_SSR), and the [Belarusian SSR](/Belarusian_SSR). [7]

Following the [Declaration of Independence of Ukraine](/Declaration_of_Independence_of_Ukraine) in 1991, Khomchak transitioned into service with the newly formed [Armed Forces of Ukraine](/Armed_Forces_of_Ukraine). From 1993 to 2000, he held positions within the [24th Mechanized Brigade](/24th_Mechanized_Brigade_(Ukraine)). [7] His career progression saw him promoted to the rank of [lieutenant-general](/Lieutenant-general) in 2013. [8]

Khomchak played a significant role in several critical engagements during the [war in Donbas](/War_in_Donbas_(2014%E2%80%932022)). He served as the sectoral commander for Ukrainian forces during the [Battle of Ilovaisk](/Battle_of_Ilovaisk). This battle proved to be a disastrous defeat for Ukrainian units, who found themselves encircled and overwhelmed by separatist forces supported by Russian military intervention. [9] Years later, reflecting on the Ilovaisk debacle, Khomchak's predecessor as Commander-in-Chief, [Viktor Muzhenko](/Viktor_Muzhenko), attributed the catastrophic outcome to a combination of factors, including the incompetence of some Ukrainian commanders and the substantial presence of Russian troops fighting alongside the separatists. [10]

On 21 May 2019, then-[President of Ukraine](/President_of_Ukraine) [Volodymyr Zelensky](/Volodymyr_Zelensky) appointed Ruslan Khomchak to the dual leadership positions of [Chief of the General Staff](/Chief_of_the_General_Staff_(Ukraine)) and Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine. [6] As previously noted, a presidential decree on 28 March 2020 separated these roles. [5] On that date, Zelensky removed Khomchak from the Chief of the General Staff position, reassigning him as Chief Commander of the Armed Forces, while [Serhiy Korniychuk](/Serhiy_Korniychuk) took over as Chief of the General Staff. [5]

Khomchak tested positive for [COVID-19](/COVID-19) on 10 September 2020. [11]

#### Family

Ruslan Khomchak is married to [Anna Kovalenko](/Anna_Kovalenko). [12] Kovalenko is a prominent figure in Ukrainian civic activism, a journalist, and a key participant in the [Euromaidan](/Euromaidan) movement. She has previously served as an advisor to three different [Ministers of Defense of Ukraine](/Minister_of_Defence_of_Ukraine) and also held the position of [Minister of Information Policy of Ukraine](/Minister_of_Information_Policy_of_Ukraine). From 13 October 2020 until 4 August 2021, she served as the [Head of the Chernihiv Regional State Administration](/Head_of_the_Chernihiv_Regional_State_Administration). [13] [14]

In January 2021, Anna Kovalenko gave birth to the couple's daughter, Maria. [12]

